<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1687,2034]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,326,1687,1713]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Observations:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A." box="[333,611,1688,1714]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="109 - 120" refId="ref68091" refString="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A. (2001) Distribucion geografica de las especies de lagartos de la Region de Antofagasta, Chile. Boletin del Museo Nacional de Historia Natural de Chile 50, 109 - 120." type="journal article" year="2001">Núñez &amp; Veloso (2001)</bibRefCitation>
provided the first record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pincheira-Donoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[941,1094,1688,1713]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multicolor">
<emphasis box="[941,1094,1688,1713]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">L. multicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Chilean territory (Salar de Aguas Calientes, 
<quantity box="[390,481,1728,1754]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="m" value="4200.0">4200 m</quantity>
, El Loa Province, 
<collectingRegion box="[696,935,1728,1754]" country="Chile" name="Antofagasta" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Antofagasta Region</collectingRegion>
). In later studies, Pincheira-Donoso (2005) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Pincheira-Donoso, D. &amp; Nunez, H." box="[201,615,1768,1794]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref69923" refString="Pincheira-Donoso, D. &amp; Nunez, H. (2005) Las especies chilenas del genero Liolaemus (Iguania, Tropiduridae, Liolaeminae). Taxonomia, sistematica y evolucion, Publicacion Ocasional del Museo Nacional de Historia Natural de Chile, Santiago, 486 pp." type="book" year="2005">Pincheira-Donoso &amp; Núñez (2005)</bibRefCitation>
cited the species for the northeastern high Andes of this country, following 
<bibRefCitation author="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A." box="[240,525,1808,1834]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="109 - 120" refId="ref68091" refString="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A. (2001) Distribucion geografica de las especies de lagartos de la Region de Antofagasta, Chile. Boletin del Museo Nacional de Historia Natural de Chile 50, 109 - 120." type="journal article" year="2001">Núñez &amp; Veloso (2001)</bibRefCitation>
. Nevertheless, a recent reassessments of the only specimen studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A." pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="109 - 120" refId="ref68091" refString="Nunez, H. &amp; Veloso, A. (2001) Distribucion geografica de las especies de lagartos de la Region de Antofagasta, Chile. Boletin del Museo Nacional de Historia Natural de Chile 50, 109 - 120." type="journal article" year="2001">Núñez &amp; Veloso (2001)</bibRefCitation>
suggests that it might be a subadult of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pincheira-Donoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[813,938,1848,1873]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="andinus">
<emphasis box="[813,938,1848,1873]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">L. andinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, field observations conducted in the populations recognized as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pincheira-Donoso" authorityYear="2005" box="[534,686,1888,1913]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multicolor">
<emphasis box="[534,686,1888,1913]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">L. multicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Pincheira-Donoso (2005) appear to support the idea that further analyses are needed to proof the existence of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[911,978,1928,1954]" name="Chile" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Chile</collectingCountry>
. Since available information as well as lizard samples are still limited, definitive conclusions are not possible at this time. Yet, the problem deserves to be reevaluated.
</paragraph>
